EBOLA UPDATE (38): COTE D'IVOIRE ex GUINEA
******************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

[1]
Date: Sun 15 Aug 2021
Source: Washington Post [edited]
https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2021/08/15/ebola-ivory-coast-guinea/


Ebola has resurfaced in Ivory Coast for the 1st time in 25 years, health officials said, after an 18-year-old woman from neighboring Guinea tested positive for the hemorrhagic fever in the nation's bustling commercial capital, Abidjan.

It is the 1st Ebola case in a major West African city since 2016. It comes about 2 months after Guinea declared the end of an outbreak that killed 12 people this year [2021] in the country and as 3rd waves of the coronavirus pummel hospitals across the region.

"It is of immense concern that this outbreak has been declared in Abidjan, a metropolis of more than 4 million people," Matshidiso Moeti, the World Health Organization's regional director for Africa, said in a statement. "However, much of the world's expertise in tackling Ebola is here on the continent."

It's unclear whether the Ivory Coast case is linked to the last epidemic, which started in February [2021] in Guinea's forested southeast -- the same region where the deadliest wave of Ebola on record erupted. That 2014-2016 outbreak killed more than 11 300 people, mostly across Guinea, Liberia, and Sierra Leone.

Health leaders in West Africa say they know how to manage the menace. Thousands of Ebola vaccine doses are on the way from Guinea, officials said late Saturday [14 Aug 2021], and health workers -- as well as people suspected to have come into contact with Ebola cases -- will receive the 1st shots.

Ivory Coast's Health Ministry said investigators are rushing to trace contracts but did not specify how many people are thought to have interacted with the young patient, who entered the country by road Wednesday [11 Aug 2021] from Labe, the 2nd-largest city in Guinea, before seeking medical help the next day [12 Aug 2021] in Abidjan.

"This is an isolated and imported case," Health Minister Pierre Dimba said in a statement.

Ebola's origin remains a mystery, but researchers suspect it probably came from bats. One of the flying mammals in Liberia tested positive for the virus in 2019.

Ivory Coast last faced Ebola in 1994, when a scientist investigating primate deaths in the Tai Forest caught the virus after conducting an autopsy on a chimpanzee, according to the US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention. The patient received treatment in Switzerland and recovered.

Scientists warn that the world will see more battles with lethal disease as deforestation pushes humans closer to animals. Another Ebola outbreak emerged this year [2021] in Congo.

Up to 90% of Ebola patients died in previous outbreaks, but health officials say chances of survival are better than ever with the rise of effective treatments. The scourge spreads mainly through body fluids.

Guinea has yet to uncover other Ebola cases. Last week, the nation reported the region's 1st brush with Marburg virus, another hemorrhagic fever with fatality rates of up to 88%, depending on the strain.

The government has ordered 155 people into 3 weeks of quarantine.

[Byline: Danielle Paquette]

