[A map of West Africa that Robert Garry kindly provided (but unfortunately cannot be reproduced here) shows the "location of the 2021 Marburg and Ebola cases. The area is a spillover zone... Lassa also is endemic in the area." The dates and cases are listed as follows:

Marburg: 1 Aug 2021 Gueckedou 1 case, 1 death
Ebola: 13 Dec 2020 Gueckedou 23K cases, 11K deaths
Ebola: Abidjan 11 Aug 2021 Ebola virus in a traveler by road from Labe, Guinea
Ebola: Goueche 14 Feb 2021 21 cases/12 deaths
Tai Forest virus: 1994 1 case/0 deaths

There are 5 subtypes of Ebola viruses: Zaire, Sudan, Bundibugyo, Tai Forest (formerly known as Cote d'Ivoire), and Reston, each named after the location in which it was first identified. The 1st 3 subtypes have been associated with large Ebolavirus disease [EVD] outbreaks in Africa. The Reston subtype is found in the Western Pacific, and although it is highly pathogenic in nonhuman primates, it is not known to cause illness in humans. Marburg virus (named after the city in Germany in which it was first discovered) is another member of the Filovirus family that also causes hemorrhagic fever. Earlier this month [August 2021], on "6 Aug 2021, the Ministry of Health of Guinea informed WHO of a confirmed case of Marburg virus disease (MVD) in Gueckedou prefecture, Nzerekore region, southwestern Guinea. The village where the case resided is near both Sierra Leone and Liberian borders. This is the 1st known case of Marburg virus disease in Guinea and in West Africa" (see Marburg virus disease - Guinea (02): (GU) conf, WHO 20210811.858593).

The virus in the case reported here was likely imported from Guinea and detected in Cote d'Ivoire. It is reported as Ebola, but the subtype has not been reported. The city in Cote d'Ivoire, Abidjan, is on the southern Atlantic coast in West Africa. It's the country's major urban center.

The Ebola outbreak that emerged in Guinea in mid-February 2021 was declared over 19 Jun 2021. But one must be concerned that there may be undetected activity in Guinea that infected this woman, or possibly sexual transmission of Ebola that has remained in the testes of a partner. Sequencing will identify Ebola subtype and possibly origin.

See Formenty P, Hatz C, Le Guenno B, et al. Human infection due to Ebola virus, subtype Cote d'Ivoire: clinical and biologic presentation. J Infect Dis. 1999;179 Suppl 1: S48-53. doi: 10.1086/514285. PMID: 9988164. The abstract follows:

Abstract
"In November 1994 after 15 years of epidemiologic silence, Ebola virus reemerged in Africa and, for the 1st time, in West Africa. In Cote d'Ivoire, a 34-year-old female ethologist was infected while conducting a necropsy on a wild chimpanzee. Eight days later, the patient developed a syndrome that did not respond to antimalarial drugs and was characterized by high fever, headache, chills, myalgia, and cough. The patient had abdominal pain, diarrhea, vomiting, and a macular rash and was repatriated to Switzerland. The patient suffered from prostration and weight loss but recovered without sequelae. Laboratory findings included aspartate aminotransferase and alanine aminotransferase activity highly elevated, thrombocytopenia, lymphopenia, and, subsequently, neutrophilia. A new subtype of Ebola was isolated from the patient's blood on days 4 and 8. No serologic conversion was detected among contact persons in Cote d'Ivoire (n = 22) or Switzerland (n = 52), suggesting that infection-control precautions were satisfactory."

Also see Formenty P, Boesch C, Wyers M, et al. Ebola virus outbreak among wild chimpanzees living in a rain forest of Cote d'Ivoire. J Infect Dis. 1999;179 Suppl 1: S120-6. doi: 10.1086/514296.

Abstract
"An outbreak of Ebola in nature is described for the 1st time. During a few weeks in November 1994, approximately 25% of 43 members of a wild chimpanzee community disappeared or were found dead in the Tai National Park, Cote d'Ivoire. A retrospective cohort study was done on the chimpanzee community. Laboratory procedures included histology, immunohistochemistry, bacteriology, and serology. Ebola-specific immunohistochemical staining was positive for autopsy tissue sections from one chimpanzee. Demographic, epidemiologic, and ecologic investigations were compatible with a point-source epidemic. Contact activities associated with a case (e.g., touching dead bodies or grooming) did not constitute significant risk factors, whereas consumption of meat did. The relative risk of meat consumption was 5.2 (95% confidence interval, 1.3-21.1). A similar outbreak occurred in November 1992 among the same community. A high mortality rate among apes tends to indicate that they are not the reservoir for the disease causing the illness. These points will have to be investigated by additional studies."
-Mod.LK

